1. Introduction to Java:
- Popular programming language, owned by Oracle. 
- Works on different platforms (Windows, Linux, Mac)
- Easy to learn, simple to use, high-level, open-source, fast, secure, huge community.
- Object oriented Programming Language. 
- Mobile, Desktop, Web, game applications 
- Write Once Run Anywhere (WORA) => Compiled code (.class file) can be run on any platform jismai JVM (based on OS) installed hai. 
- Terms and its meanings:- (JAVA FEATURES)
    - Secure -> java restricts direct access to underlying memory or OS to avoid unauthorised access and memory corruption.
    - Portable -> Same code written in Windows machine can be executed in Linux/MacOS machine without any changes. 
    - Robust -> java provides strong compile time checks for syntax and structures and runtime error handling to avoid crashes.
    - Dynamic -> adapts to evolving env. 
        -> stores more runtime info than c and c++ which solves object access related issues.
    - Multithreading -> Multiple threads concurrently run kar rahe hote hai to accomplish sub-tasks of a single process 
        -> Shared Memory hota hai 
        -> Fast Communication 
        -> Challenges:- Deadlock, Race Condition etc 
        -> eg.  YT application (process)
            -> T1 - video play 
            -> T2 - comments show 
            -> T3 - loading further video    
            Teeno threads parallely kaam kar rahe hain in a single process.  
    - Multiprocessing -> Multiple independent processes ek sath run karna. 
        -> No shared memory. 
        -> More Safe than multi-threading but its heavier. 
        -> like chrome, vs code ek sath chalana.
    - Distributed -> Multiple computers ek sath milke kam kar rahe hain to complete a task.  
        -> Bigger problem is divided into multiple smaller ones. 
        -> Each machine works on one smaller problem. 
        -> All results are then merged to get the desired result. 
        -> eg: Google Search 
            -> Different servers ke query krte hain
            -> Unke results ko combine karke hame result milta hai. 
        -> Highly used for scalability and fault-tolerance. 
            -> Data is also distributed and stored accross multiple machines. 
            -> Even replicas are stored.  

2. JAVA vs C++
- Java is platform independent. compiled code can be run anywhere provided the machine has JVM. 
  C++ is machine dependent. If .exe file is generated in Windows, can't run it in Linux.
  
- Java mai object management is done automatically.
  C++ mai we need to do it more manually (new, delete) 

- Java support concepts of threads but C++ doesn't.
- Java doesn't have goto keyword. uses break/continue to move to certain part. 
- Java doesn't provide global scope like C++. has package scope instead. 

